ife During Wartime\"\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Second-Hand Suit Jacket Racket'' || Lookout || \"Letter from an Old Friend\"\n|}\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n* [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] - guitar, vocals <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Aaron Cometbus]] - [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Bill Schneider (musician)|Bill Schneider]] - [[Bass guitar|bass]], vocals <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]] - [[guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]] <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Former members\n* [[Sarah Kirsch (musician)|Sarah Kirsch]] - guitar, vocals <small>(1990\u20131994; died 2012)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.punknews.org/bands/pinheadgunpowder Pinhead Gunpowder profile at Punknews.org (Reviews, News, Biography)]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/pinheadgunpowderusa Pinhead Gunpowder] on [[MySpace]]\n\n{{Pinhead Gunpowder}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Punk rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Adeline Records artists]]\n[[Category:Recess Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the band|the green tea variety|Gunpowder tea}}\n{{Primary sources|date=July 2008}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Pinhead Gunpowder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[East Bay, California]]\n| genre               = [[Punk rock]], [[garage rock]]\n| years_active        = 1991\u2013present\n| label               = [[Lookout! Records|Lookout!]], [[Adeline Records|Adeline]], [[Recess Records|Recess]]\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Green Day]]\n* [[Foxboro Hot Tubs]]\n* [[The Network]]\n* [[The Influents]]\n* [[Crimpshrine]]\n* [[Monsula]]\n* [[Screeching Weasel]]\n* Chino Horde\n* California\n* The Coverups\n}}\n| website                 = \n| current_members     = \n* [[Billie Joe Armstrong]]\n* [[Bill Schneider (musician)|Bill Schneider]]\n* [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]]\n* [[Aaron Cometbus]]\n| past_members        = \n* Sarah Kirsch<!--Do not reference Kirsch's passing here.-->\n}}\n'''Pinhead Gunpowder''' is an American [[punk rock]] band that formed in [[East Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|East Bay]], [[California]], in 1990. The band currently consists of [[Aaron Cometbus]] ([[Drum kit|drums]], [[lyrics]]), [[Bill Schneider (musician)|Bill Schneider]] ([[Bass guitar|bass]]), [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] ([[guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]]) and [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]] ([[guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]]). The band's name comes from a brand of \"high octane\" green tea served at the [[Arcata]] co-op and discovered by Aaron Cometbus during one of his many [[dumpster diving]] adventures.\n\n==History==\nPinhead Gunpowder was founded in Arcata, California, in January 1991 by Aaron Cometbus and Jon Quittner. Cometbus wanted the name \"Pinhead Gunpowder\", while Quittner wanted to call it \"50 Foot Hesher\". Along with vocalist Doug \"Douggie Grime\" Rogers and bassist David \"Atlas\" Kimmel, the band played once at a party where Cometbus snapped his bass pedal in half in the middle of the set. Shortly after the show, Cometbus moved back to Berkeley, taking the name of the band and some of the songs with him. Quittner stayed in Arcata with the band and they changed their name to 50 Foot Hesher and acquired a new drummer. A few months later, Quittner left the band and the remaining members changed the name to \"Lank\". \n\nBack in Berkeley, Cometbus formed the second incarnation of Pinhead Gunpowder with Bill Schneider and Sarah Kirsch of The Skinflutes, and Billie Joe Armstrong of [[Green Day]] . In June 1991 they recorded their first EP, ''Tr\u00fcndle and Spring''. It wasn't until April of the following year that the band played their first live show at Punks With Presses in Oakland along with Rancid and The Gr'Ups. The band then released their second EP, ''Fahizah''. In 1993, Kirsch left the band citing personal differences with Armstrong's decision to sign to a major label with Green Day.  Kirsch was replaced by Jason White of Chino Horde. Shortly after, the band embarked on a week long tour of Northern California, Oregon, and Washington in the winter of 1994. \n\n==Current==\nPinhead Gunpowder performed for the first time in many years during February 2008, debuting three new songs, \"Anniversary Song\", \"West Side Highway\", and \"On the Ave\" .\n\nThe band released their latest EP, ''[[Pinhead Gunpowder (2008 EP)|West Side Highway]]'' through [[Recess Records]] on August 19, 2008. This marked the band's first new release in 5 years.\n\nPinhead Gunpowder released a greatest hits album called ''[[Kick Over the Traces]]'' on June 19, 2009. Also, Pinhead Gunpowder mentioned that in August or September Recess would re-release on vinyl and CD the albums ''[[Jump Salty]]'', ''[[Carry the Banner]]'', ''[[Goodbye Ellston Avenue]]'', ''[[Shoot the Moon (EP)|Shoot the Moon]]'' and ''[[Compulsive Disclosure]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/index.php?subaction=showcomments&id=1233810000&archive= |title=Green Day Authority |publisher=Green Day Authority |date= |accessdate=2011-11-01}}</ref> All of the albums were re-released in assorted colors in early February 2010 through Recess Records, but quickly recalled and destroyed at the request of the band. The band last performed at a benefit show at [[924 Gilman Street]] in Berkeley, California on February 12, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/216 |title=Pinhead Gunpowder album reissues |publisher=Greendayauthority.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/217 |title=Pinhead Gunpowder show recap |publisher=Greendayauthority.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==Songwriting==\nAaron Cometbus is the primary writer of Pinhead Gunpowder's songs. During Pinhead Gunpowder's first incarnation, Cometbus and Quittner wrote a handful of songs together, including \"In Control\", \"Losers of the Year\", \"Certain Things\", \"Brother\", \"I Used To\", \"Stab You in the Eye\", and \"Cuidado\" (The last two songs released by Quittner and Cometbus under the band name \"Mundt\"). Cometbus often borrows songs recorded by his other bands to release as Pinhead Gunpowder songs, including \"Train Station\" from Shotwell Coho, \"The Great Divide\" from Redmond Shooting Stars, \"Asheville\" from Cleveland Bound Death Sentence, and \"On the Ave\" and \"Landlords\" from Astrid Oto. Only three Pinhead Gunpowder songs have been written by Billie Joe Armstrong, under the name \"Wilhelm Fink\". Those are \"27\", \"New Blood\", and \"Anniversary Song\". \n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Title || Label\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Goodbye Ellston Avenue]]'' || [[Lookout Records|Lookout]]/[[Recess Records|Recess]]\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Label\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Tr\u00fcndle and Spring]]'' || Take a Day\n|-\n| 1992 || ''[[Fahizah]]'' || Lookout\n|-\n| 1994 || ''[[Carry the Banner]]'' || [[Very Small Records|Too Many]]/Lookout/Recess\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Shoot the Moon (EP)|Shoot the Moon]]'' || [[Adeline Records|Adeline]]/Recess\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Dillinger Four / Pinhead Gunpowder]]'' || Adeline\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Pinhead Gunpowder (2000 EP)|Pinhead Gunpowder]]'' || THD\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[8 Chords, 328 Words]]'' || Lookout\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Pinhead Gunpowder (2008 EP)|West Side Highway]]'' || Recess \n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Title || Label\n|-\n| 1994 || ''[[Jump Salty]]'' || LookoutRecess Records|Recess\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Compulsive Disclosure]]'' || Lookout/Recess\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Kick Over the Traces]]'' || Recess\n|}\n\n===Compilation appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Title || Label || Contributing track\n|-\n| 1991 || ''Very Small World'' || [[Very Small Records|Very Small]] || \"Losers of the Year\"\n|-\n| 1992 || ''Can of Pork'' || Lookout || \"Benicia by the Bay\"\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Benicia'' || Take a Day || \"Benicia by the Bay\"\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Vinyl Retentive'' || Very Small || \"Beastly Bit\"\n|-\n| 1994 || ''Misfit Heartbeat'' || Take a Day || \"I Wanna\"\n|-\n| 1996 || ''Lookout Records'' || Lookout || \"I Am the Stranger\"\n|-\n| 1997 || ''Humans as Sewage'' || BBT Tapes || \"Swan Song (live)\", \"Reach for the Bottle (live)\", \"Nigel Sings\"\n|-\n| 1997 || ''The Last Great Thing You Did'' || Lookout || \"Life During Wartime\"\n|-\n| 2000 || ''Faux Pas Potpourri - Very Small Records '93-'99'' || Very Small || \"Reach for the Bottle (live)\"\n|-\n| 2000 || ''Might as Well... Can't Dance'' || Adeline || \"Porch\"\n|-\n| 2001 || ''Down in Front'' || No Idea || \"Beastly Bit (acoustic)\", \"Reach for the Bottle (live)\", \"Swan Song (live)\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''Then Is the New Now'' || Lookout || \"At Your Funeral\", \"Life During Wartime\"\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Second-Hand Suit Jacket Racket'' || Lookout || \"Letter from an Old Friend\"\n|}\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n* [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] - guitar, vocals <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Aaron Cometbus]] - [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Bill Schneider (musician)|Bill Schneider]] - [[Bass guitar|bass]], vocals <small>(1990\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]] - [[guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]] <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Former members\n* [[Sarah Kirsch (musician)|Sarah Kirsch]] - guitar, vocals <small>(1990\u20131994; died 2012)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.punknews.org/bands/pinheadgunpowder Pinhead Gunpowder profile at Punknews.org (Reviews, News, Biography)]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/pinheadgunpowderusa Pinhead Gunpowder] on [[MySpace]]\n\n{{Pinhead Gunpowder}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Punk rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Adeline Records artists]]\n[[Category:Recess Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Markoff-Chaney", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinhead_Gunpowder"}
{"title_page": "List of Southern Conference football champions", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Infobox NCAA conference tournament\n| name               = Southern Conference football champions\n| optional_subheader = Conference Football Champions\n| defunct            = \n| image              = [[File:Southern Conference logo.svg|100px]]\n| caption            = Southern Conference logo\n| sport              = [[College football]]\n| conference         = [[Southern Conference]]\n| number_of_teams    = <!-- Not relevant, not a tournament -->\n| format             = <!-- Not relevant -->\n| current_stadium    = <!-- Not relevant -->\n| current_location   = <!-- Not relevant -->\n| years              = 1933\u2013present\n| most_recent        = \n| current_champion   = Wofford<ref>http://www.espn.co.uk/college-football/team/_/id/2747/wofford-terriers</ref>\n| most_championships = Furman (13)\n| television         = [[SportSouth]]<br>[[American Sports Network]]\n| website            = [http://www.soconsports.com/SportSelect.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4000&SPID=1781&SPSID=21895 SoConSports.com Football]\n| sponsors           = \n| all_stadiums       = <!-- Not relevant -->\n| all_locations      = <!-- Not relevant -->\n}}\nThe list of '''Southern Conference football champions''' includes 20 distinct teams that have won the [[college football]] championship awarded by the [[Southern Conference]] since its creation. In total, forty-one teams have sponsored football in the conference.<ref>Current member [[University of North Carolina at Greensboro|UNC Greensboro]] does not sponsor football.</ref> Just two \u2014Mercer and Western Carolina\u2014have never won a Southern Conference football championship.\n\nThe conference was formed in 1921 when fourteen members from the [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SIAA) met in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] with the purpose of creating a workable number of conference games for each member.<ref name=\"SoConH\">{{cite news|title=The History of the Southern Conference|author=Southern Conference|date=2008-06-30|accessdate=2008-07-25|url=http://www.soconsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4000&KEY=&ATCLID=177772}}</ref> The Southern Conference is notable for having spawned two other major conferences. In 1933, thirteen schools located south and west of the [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachians]] ([[University of Alabama|Alabama]], [[Auburn University|Auburn]], [[University of Florida|Florida]], [[University of Georgia|Georgia]], [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]], [[University of Kentucky|Kentucky]], [[Louisiana State University|LSU]], [[University of Mississippi|Mississippi]], [[Mississippi State University|Mississippi State]], [[Sewanee: The University of the South|Sewanee]], [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], [[Tulane University|Tulane]], and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt]]) departed to form the [[Southeastern Conference]].<ref name=\"SECHistory\">{{cite news|title=About the Southeastern Conference (SEC) |author=Southeastern Conference |date=2007 |accessdate=2008-07-23 |url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&change_well_id=9993 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616223143/http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&change_well_id=9993 |archivedate=2008-06-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Twenty years later, in 1953, seven schools ([[Clemson University|Clemson]], [[Duke University|Duke]], [[University of Maryland, College Park|Maryland]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|North Carolina]], [[North Carolina State University|North Carolina State]], [[University of South Carolina|South Carolina]], and [[Wake Forest University|Wake Forest]]) withdrew to form the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]].<ref name=\"ACCHistory\">{{cite news|title=About the ACC |author=Atlantic Coast Conference |date=2008 |accessdate=2008-07-25 |url=http://www.theacc.com/this-is/acc-this-is.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014033802/http://www.theacc.com/this-is/acc-this-is.html |archivedate=2012-10-14 }}</ref>\n\nCurrently the conference competes at the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] level in athletics, with the football teams playing in the [[Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS). There are nine football playing members of the Southern Conference:[[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga|Chattanooga]], [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina|The Citadel]], [[East Tennessee State University|East Tennessee State]], [[Furman University|Furman]], [[Mercer University|Mercer]], [[Samford University|Samford]], [[Virginia Military Institute]], [[Western Carolina University|Western Carolina]], and [[Wofford College|Wofford]]. Southern Conference teams have been successful in the NCAA Division I FCS Playoffs, leading all conferences with an 87\u201349 (.640) record.<ref name=\"Weekly\">{{cite news|title=Southern Conference Football: SoCon Playoff History|author=Southern Conference|date=2008-12-01|accessdate=2008-12-16|url=http://www.soconsports.com/pdf5/355095.pdf?ATCLID=1567928&SPSID=31927&SPID=1781&DB_OEM_ID=4000}}</ref> Current and former Southern Conference teams have won a total of 12 [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|national championships]].<ref name=\"Weekly\"/>x\n\n==Champions by year==\n\n===Undefeated teams claiming championships: 1922\u20131932===\nThe Southern Conference does not officially recognize championships claimed from the 1922\u201332 seasons,<ref name=\"FBProfile\">{{cite news|title=Football Record Book|work=2005 Southern Conference Football|author=Southern Conference|page=144|accessdate=2008-06-10|url=http://www.soconsports.com/pdf6/20783.pdf?SPSID=37278&SPID=1781&ATCLID=201460&DB_OEM_ID=4000}}</ref> as there were upwards of 20 to 23 teams competing within the conference during this time. However, some championships are still cited and claimed by the individual schools.\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Undefeated team(s)<ref name=\"SoConLeaders\">{{cite news|title=Annual Leaders, History|work=2008 Southern Conference Football Media Guide|author=Southern Conference|pages=168\u2013171|date=2008-08-06|accessdate=2008-12-16|url=http://www.soconsports.com/fls/4000/socon/files/08fbguide/annualleaders.pdf?SPSID=35576&SPID=1781&DB_OEM_ID=4000}}</ref>\n! Conference Record\n! Notes\n</center>\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1922 college football season|1922]]\n|[[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]]<br />[[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]]<br /> [[1922 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]\n|4\u20130<br />5\u20130<br /> 3\u20130\n|This was the inaugural Southern Conference football season with 20 teams participating. Vanderbilt was also a member of the SIAA until 1924, and defeated both [[1922 Sewanee Tigers football team|Sewanee]] and [[Mercer Bears football|Mercer]]. Vanderbilt tied [[1922 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] 0-0 at the [[1922 Michigan vs. Vanderbilt football game|dedication]] of [[Dudley Field]]. [[1922 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] [[upset (sports)|upset]] [[1922 Centre Praying Colonels football team|Centre]], previously undefeated in conference play. Vanderbilt [[End (American football)|end]] [[Lynn Bomar]] and Tech [[running back]] [[Red Barron]] were unanimous All-Southern and [[Walter Camp]] All-America second-team.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1923 college football season|1923]]\n|[[1923 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]<br />[[Washington and Lee Generals football|Washington and Lee]]\n| 3\u20130\u20131<br />4\u20130\u20131\n|[[1923 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] upset  [[1923 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], previously undefeated in conference play. Board of sportswriters awarded Vanderbilt the [[Champ Pickens]] trophy as Southern champions.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Washington Post|title=Vanderbilt Is Named For Pickens Trophy|date=December 2, 1923|id = {{ProQuest|149383922}}}}</ref>\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1924 college football season|1924]]\n|[[1924 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|5\u20130\n|Board of sportswriters awarded Alabama the Champ Pickens trophy as Southern champions.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1925 college football season|1925]]\n|[[1925 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]<br /> [[1925 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n|7\u20130<br /> 5\u20130\n|Alabama wins [[NCAA Division I-A National Football Championship|national championship]];<ref name=\"Tide\">{{cite web|title=Traditions: National Championships |author=Alabama Athletics |accessdate=2008-07-25 |url=http://www.rolltide.com/trads/national-championships.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022183419/http://www.rolltide.com/trads/national-championships.html |archivedate=2008-10-22 }}</ref> the first Southern team to win a [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]]. Board of sportswriters awarded Alabama the Champ Pickens trophy as Southern champions.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1926 college football season|1926]]\n|[[1926 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|8\u20130\n|Alabama wins national championship.<ref name=\"Tide\"/> Board of sportswriters awarded Alabama the Champ Pickens trophy as Southern champions.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1927 college football season|1927]]\n|[[1927 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]]<br />[[1927 NC State Wolfpack football team|NC State]]<br />[[1927 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]]\n|7\u20130\u20131<br /> 4\u20130<br />5\u20130\u20131\n|Georgia Tech upset Georgia's \"[[1927 Georgia Bulldogs football team|dream and wonder team]]\" in its final game. Georgia had beaten Yale, and had it defeated Tech it would have been national champion; and still some selectors claim them as such.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1928 college football season|1928]]\n|[[1928 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]]\n|7\u20130\n|Georgia Tech wins national championship.<ref name=\"Tech\">{{cite web|title=Georgia Tech Titles|author=Georgia Tech Athletics|accessdate=2008-06-10|url=http://ramblinwreck.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/titles.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405180854/http://ramblinwreck.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/titles.html|archive-date=2008-04-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1929 college football season|1929]]\n|[[1929 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n|6\u20130\n|\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1930 college football season|1930]]\n|[[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]<br /> [[1930 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n|8\u20130<br /> 5\u20130\n|Alabama wins national championship .<ref name=\"Tide\"/>\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1931 college football season|1931]]\n|[[1931 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n|8\u20130\n|Tulane lost the Rose Bowl to USC.\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1932 college football season|1932]]\n|[[1932 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]<br /> [[1932 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]<br />[[1932 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]]\n|6\u20130\u20131<br /> 4\u20130 <br />7\u20130\u20131\n|Thirteen teams leave after this season to form the [[Southeastern Conference]].<ref name=\"SECHistory\"/>\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Champions: 1933\u2013present===\nIn 1978 Division I football was split into two classifications: the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (formerly I-A) and [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Football Championship Subdivision]] (formerly I-AA). The Southern Conference moved to the FCS in 1982 where its members compete for the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship]].\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Champion(s)<ref name=\"SoConLeaders\"/>\n! Conference Record\n! Notes\n</center>\n|-align=\"center\"\n|[[1933 college football season|1933]]\n|[[Duke Blue Devils football|Duke]]\n|4\u20130\n|Upset defending Southern champion 